wn from and occupied with amatory and ethical traditions, and their discourse produces a series of attempts to find a coherent and rational union of lover and ruler. The volume also argues that Gower's goal is poetic as well as political: through the personae, Gower's readers experience the pains and pleasures of erotic and social love. Gower's personae voice potential responses to exemplary experience, prompting readers to feel and to judge, and moving them to become better lovers and better rulers. Gower's analogy between fin amour and politics brings the affects of the lover to the action of government, and suggests for both love and rule the moderation that brings peace and joy. Matthew W. Irvin is Assistant Professor in the Department of English and Chair of the Medieval Studies Program at Sewanee.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aConfessio Amantis.  aEnglish Literature.  aEthical Traditions.  aJohn Gower.  aLiterary Influence.  aLiterature Analysis.  aLiterature and Politics.  aLove.  aMedieval Literature.  aPersonae.  aPoetic Voices.  aPolitical Ethics.  aPolitics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204206840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782042068423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782042068/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles